{"title_page": "Oakwood Park Grammar School", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox school \n| name          = Oakwood Park Grammar School\n| image         = Oakwood Park Grammar School logo.jpg\n| image_size          = 200px\n| coordinates   = {{coord|51.270|0.499|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| motto         = Strive and Serve\n| established   = 1918\n| closed        = \n| type          = [[Grammar School]];<br>[[Academy (English school)|Academy]]\n| religious_affiliation      = \n| president     = \n| head_label    = Headmaster\n| head          = Kevin Moody\n| r_head_label  = \n| r_head        = \n| chair_label   = Chairman of Governors\n| chair         = J. Murton\n| founder       = \n| address        = Oakwood Park\n| city          = [[Maidstone]]\n| county        = [[Kent]]\n| country       = United Kingdom\n| postcode      = ME16 8AH\n| ofsted        = yes\n| dfeno         = 886/5422\n| urn           = 136727\n| staff         = 65\n| enrolment    = 994<ref name=\"about\"/>\n| gender        = Boys (co-ed Sixth Form)\n| lower_age     = 11\n| upper_age     = 18\n| houses        = Broughton, Fisher, Hazlitt, Sadler, Wilberforce\n| colours       = Maroon and blue\n| publication   = @Oakwood\n| free_label_1  = \n| free_1        = \n| free_label_2  = \n| free_2        = \n| free_label_3  = \n| free_3        = \n| website       = http://www.opgs.org/\n}}\n\n'''Oakwood Park Grammar School''' is a [[Single-sex education|boys]] [[grammar school]] with [[Academy (English school)|academy status]] located in [[Maidstone]], United Kingdom. The school is co-educational in the [[sixth form]] (years 12 and 13). The school takes boys at the age of 11 and over by [[eleven-plus exam|examination (11-plus)]] and boys and girls at 16+ on their [[GCSE]] results. The current headteacher is Kevin Moody. The school is popularly known by its initials '''OPGS''' or simply '''Oakwood'''.\n\n==History==\nOPGS was founded in 1918 as the '''Co-educational Junior Technical School for Boys and the Junior Commercial School for Girls'''.<ref name=\"lewis\">{{cite journal|last=Lewis|first=Jon|title=A rose by any other name|publisher=Oakwood Park Grammar School|year=2009}}</ref> The school was based at two sites in Maidstone town centre: Faith Street and Tonbridge Road. The school admitted pupils at the age of 11 and 13. The school was also known as the '''Maidstone Technical School.'''\n\nBy the 1950s the school had outgrown these two sites and a new site was found at Oakwood Park, further along on the Tonbridge Road. The school moved into its new premises between September 1958 and September 1959.<ref name=\"about\">{{cite web|title=About Oakwood Park |url=http://www.opgs.org/aboutus.htm|work=School|publisher=Oakwood Park Grammar School}}</ref><ref name=\"lewis\"/> The new premises were officially opened in September 1959 with a service of dedication performed by the then [[Archbishop of Canterbury]] [[Geoffrey Francis Fisher]]. It was then known as the '''Maidstone Technical School for Boys'''. In 1963 it became the '''Maidstone Technical High School for Boys'''.\n\nThe introduction of [[comprehensive education]] in the 1970s lead to the ''Thameside Scheme'' being introduced in the Maidstone area.<ref name=\"lewis\"/> September 1971 saw the last admission at age of 11. There were no new admissions in the next two academic years. From September 1974 pupils were admitted at the age of 13. At the same time the school was renamed '''Maidstone School for Boys'''.<ref name=\"lewis\"/> Under the ''Thameside Scheme'' technical schools had in effect become [[grammar schools]] but were not allowed to call themselves as such. Now the school had to compete with [[Maidstone Grammar School]] for pupils.\n\nIn 1983 the use of the \"grammar school\" title was relaxed and on 10 October 1983 Maidstone School for Boys became '''Oakwood Park Grammar School'''.<ref name=\"lewis\"/><ref>{{cite book|last=Yates|first=Nigel|title=Kent in the twentieth century|year=2001|publisher=Kent County Council|pages=314|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6sQjOlwvyNcC}}</ref> In the 1980s the school started admitting girls into the sixth form.\n\nEnrolment declined in the late 1980s and [[Kent County Council]], the local education authority, considered merging OPGS with [[Invicta Grammar School]], a girls grammar school located in east Maidstone. A vigorous campaign by parents, staff and governors prevented the merger. On 1 April 1992 OPGS became one of the first schools in the area to achieve [[grant maintained]] status, giving it independence from KCC. Enrolment increased thereafter and in September 1993 grammar schools across the area started admitting pupils at the age of 11 (year 7).{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n\nAfter the scrapping of grant maintained status in the late 1990s, OPGS became a community school, reverting to KCC control. The school became a [[Mathematics and Computing College|mathematics and computing specialist college]] in 2003.<ref name=\"about\"/> The school then became a [[foundation school]], giving it some independence from Kent County Council. On 1 May 2011 the school officially became an [[Academy (English school)|academy]], meaning that Kent County Council no longer have any responsibility for the school apart from co-ordinating admissions.\n\n==Extracurricular activities==\nOPGS's extracurricular activities are extensive and varied. The school has sports teams in football, rugby, cricket, basketball, rowing and athletics which compete at local, county and national levels.<ref name=\"ec\">{{cite web|title=Extra Curricular |url=http://www.opgs.org/extra.htm|work=School|publisher=Oakwood Park Grammar School}}</ref> There are regular inter-form competitions and an annual sports day. The school has numerous music groups including an orchestra and the ''Coconut Grove'' steel band.<ref name=\"ec\"/> The school has a purpose-built drama studio which is home to the drama club.<ref name=\"ec\"/> Other school clubs include debating, chess and robotics.<ref name=\"ec\"/> The school is a participant in the [[Duke of Edinburgh Award]] scheme and has numerous overseas trips.<ref name=\"ec\"/> Oakwood focus on these aspects greatly and it is very unusual for a grammar school to emphasise the importance of extracurricular work. This is also done though volunteering day which is held each year and in which all students volunteer for one school day to gain experience and to give back to the community.\n\n==Houses==\nOPGS used to have houses named after local villages \u2013 Allington, Brenchley, Chillington, Charing, Detling, Egerton and Farleigh. This house system was abandoned in the 1980s.\n\nThe house system was re-introduced in 2009 due to the school's growing size and to accompany the school's 50-year anniversary. The school's five houses are:<ref>{{cite web|title=House System |url=http://www.opgs.org/houses.htm|work=Community|publisher=Oakwood Park Grammar School}}</ref>\n* Broughton (named after [[Andrew Broughton]], former Mayor of Maidstone and signatory of [[Charles I of England]]'s death warrant)\n* Fisher (named after [[Geoffrey Francis Fisher]], [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], who led the dedication service at the official opening of the school's Oakwood Park site)\n* Hazlitt (named after [[William Hazlitt]], a famous English essayist, playwright and social commentator who was from Maidstone)\n* Sadler (named after [[David Sadler (footballer)|David Sadler]], a former OPGS student who went on to play 272 games for [[Manchester United]] football club following the devastating [[Munich air disaster]], and 4 games for England)\n* Wilberforce (named after [[William Wilberforce]], the famous British politician who successfully stood against slavery, who has family in [[East Farleigh]])\n\n==Headmasters==\n* 2006 \u2013 Kevin W. Moody\n* 1992 \u2013 2006 Mike J. Newbould\n* 1985 \u2013 1992 A. G. Sandford\n* 1966 \u2013 1985 John A. Skinner\n* 1956 \u2013 1966 R. H. Voice\n* 1933 \u2013 1955 H. Collins\n* 1918 \u2013 1933 James Quick\n\n==Alumni==\nOPGS has helped nurture students through various career paths.\n* [[James Hall (gymnast)|James Hall]] Artistic gymnast<ref name=\"James Hall\">{{cite web|title=James Hall |url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/oakwood-park-pupil-james-hall-ha-a56625}}</ref>\n* [[David Sadler (footballer)|David Sadler]] A footballer for Manchester United\n* [[Dominic Sherwood]] Actor, known for his roles in [[Shadowhunters]] and [[Vampire Academy (film)|Vampire Academy]]\n* Laurie Vincent Musician, known for playing Guitar, Bass and Vocals in the band [[Slaves (UK band)|Slaves]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/slaves-nominated-for-bbc-music-sound-of-2015-28022/|title=Maidstone band shortlisted for prestigious award|work=Kent Online|access-date=17 April 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Marc Morris]] Historian\n* [[Mark Sargeant]] Michelin starred chef\n\n==Sex Tape==\nOPGS hit the headlines on 22 June 1995 when pupils using a 'blank' VHS tape for a project found it contained footage of a male chemistry teacher and a female physics teacher engaging in sexual acts in the school's gymnasium. Pupils reportedly had to be instructed not to speak to the sizeable number of journalists who congregated at the school gates.<ref>{{cite news|title=Teachers axed for sex video|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/salamandertome/3319960197/sizes/l/in/set-72157614630872064/|newspaper=[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]|date=22 June 1995}}</ref>\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.opgs.org Oakwood Park Grammar School website]\n* [http://www.opgs.net/ Oakwood Park Grammar School alumni network]\n\n{{Schools in Kent}}\n\n[[Category:Grammar schools in Kent]]\n[[Category:Boys' schools in Kent]]\n[[Category:Maidstone]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1918]]\n[[Category:1918 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Academies in Kent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox school \n| name          = Oakwood Park Grammar School\n| image         = Oakwood Park Grammar School logo.jpg\n| image_size          = 200px\n| coordinates   = {{coord|51.270|0.499|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| motto         = Strive and Serve\n| established   = 1918\n| closed        = \n| type          = [[Grammar School]];<br>[[Academy (English school)|Academy]]\n| religious_affiliation      = \n| president     = \n| head_label    = Headmaster\n| head          = Kevin Moody\n| r_head_label  = \n| r_head        = \n| chair_label   = Chairman of Governors\n| chair         = J. Murton\n| founder       = \n| address        = Oakwood Park\n| city          = [[Maidstone]]\n| county        = [[Kent]]\n| country       = United Kingdom\n| postcode      = ME16 8AH\n| ofsted        = yes\n| dfeno         = 886/5422\n| urn           = 136727\n| staff         = 65\n| enrolment    = 994<ref name=\"about\"/>\n| gender        = Boys (co-ed Sixth Form)\n| lower_age     = 11\n| upper_age     = 18\n| houses        = Broughton, Fisher, Hazlitt, Sadler, Wilberforce\n| colours       = Maroon and blue\n| publication   = @Oakwood\n| free_label_1  = \n| free_1        = \n| free_label_2  = \n| free_2        = \n| free_label_3  = \n| free_3        = \n| website       = http://www.opgs.org/\n}}\n\n'''Oakwood Park Grammar School''' is a [[Single-sex education|boys]] [[grammar school]] with [[Academy (English school)|academy status]] located in [[Maidstone]], United Kingdom. The school is co-educational in the [[sixth form]] (years 12 and 13). The school takes boys at the age of 11 and over by [[eleven-plus exam|examination (11-plus)]] and boys and girls at 16+ on their [[GCSE]] results. The current headteacher is Kevin Moody. The school is popularly known by its initials '''OPGS''' or simply '''Oakwood'''.\n\n==History==\nOPGS was founded in 1918 as the '''Co-educational Junior Technical School for Boys and the Junior Commercial School for Girls'''.<ref name=\"lewis\">{{cite journal|last=Lewis|first=Jon|title=A rose by any other name|publisher=Oakwood Park Grammar School|year=2009}}</ref> The school was based at two sites in Maidstone town centre: Faith Street and Tonbridge Road. The school admitted pupils at the age of 11 and 13. The school was also known as the '''Maidstone Technical School.'''\n\nBy the 1950s the school had outgrown these two sites and a new site was found at Oakwood Park, further along on the Tonbridge Road. The school moved into its new premises between September 1958 and September 1959.<ref name=\"about\">{{cite web|title=About Oakwood Park |url=http://www.opgs.org/aboutus.htm|work=School|publisher=Oakwood Park Grammar School}}</ref><ref name=\"lewis\"/> The new premises were officially opened in September 1959 with a service of dedication performed by the then [[Archbishop of Canterbury]] [[Geoffrey Francis Fisher]]. It was then known as the '''Maidstone Technical School for Boys'''. In 1963 it became the '''Maidstone Technical High School for Boys'''.\n\nThe introduction of [[comprehensive education]] in the 1970s lead to the ''Thameside Scheme'' being introduced in the Maidstone area.<ref name=\"lewis\"/> September 1971 saw the last admission at age of 11. There were no new admissions in the next two academic years. From September 1974 pupils were admitted at the age of 13. At the same time the school was renamed '''Maidstone School for Boys'''.<ref name=\"lewis\"/> Under the ''Thameside Scheme'' technical schools had in effect become [[grammar schools]] but were not allowed to call themselves as such. Now the school had to compete with [[Maidstone Grammar School]] for pupils.\n\nIn 1983 the use of the \"grammar school\" title was relaxed and on 10 October 1983 Maidstone School for Boys became '''Oakwood Park Grammar School'''.<ref name=\"lewis\"/><ref>{{cite book|last=Yates|first=Nigel|title=Kent in the twentieth century|year=2001|publisher=Kent County Council|pages=314|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6sQjOlwvyNcC}}</ref> In the 1980s the school started admitting girls into the sixth form.\n\nEnrolment declined in the late 1980s and [[Kent County Council]], the local education authority, considered merging OPGS with [[Invicta Grammar School]], a girls grammar school located in east Maidstone. A vigorous campaign by parents, staff and governors prevented the merger. On 1 April 1992 OPGS became one of the first schools in the area to achieve [[grant maintained]] status, giving it independence from KCC. Enrolment increased thereafter and in September 1993 grammar schools across the area started admitting pupils at the age of 11 (year 7).{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n\nAfter the scrapping of grant maintained status in the late 1990s, OPGS became a community school, reverting to KCC control. The school became a [[Mathematics and Computing College|mathematics and computing specialist college]] in 2003.<ref name=\"about\"/> The school then became a [[foundation school]], giving it some independence from Kent County Council. On 1 May 2011 the school officially became an [[Academy (English school)|academy]], meaning that Kent County Council no longer have any responsibility for the school apart from co-ordinating admissions.\n\n==Extracurricular activities==\nOPGS's extracurricular activities are extensive and varied. The school has sports teams in football, rugby, cricket, basketball, rowing and athletics which compete at local, county and national levels.<ref name=\"ec\">{{cite web|title=Extra Curricular |url=http://www.opgs.org/extra.htm|work=School|publisher=Oakwood Park Grammar School}}</ref> There are regular inter-form competitions and an annual sports day. The school has numerous music groups including an orchestra and the ''Coconut Grove'' steel band.<ref name=\"ec\"/> The school has a purpose-built drama studio which is home to the drama club.<ref name=\"ec\"/> Other school clubs include debating, chess and robotics.<ref name=\"ec\"/> The school is a participant in the [[Duke of Edinburgh Award]] scheme and has numerous overseas trips.<ref name=\"ec\"/> Oakwood focus on these aspects greatly and it is very unusual for a grammar school to emphasise the importance of extracurricular work. This is also done though volunteering day which is held each year and in which all students volunteer for one school day to gain experience and to give back to the community.\n\n==Houses==\nOPGS used to have houses named after local villages \u2013 Allington, Brenchley, Charing, Detling, Egerton and Farleigh. This house system was abandoned in the 1980s.\n\nThe house system was re-introduced in 2009 due to the school's growing size and to accompany the school's 50-year anniversary. The school's five houses are:<ref>{{cite web|title=House System |url=http://www.opgs.org/houses.htm|work=Community|publisher=Oakwood Park Grammar School}}</ref>\n* Broughton (named after [[Andrew Broughton]], former Mayor of Maidstone and signatory of [[Charles I of England]]'s death warrant)\n* Fisher (named after [[Geoffrey Francis Fisher]], [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], who led the dedication service at the official opening of the school's Oakwood Park site)\n* Hazlitt (named after [[William Hazlitt]], a famous English essayist, playwright and social commentator who was from Maidstone)\n* Sadler (named after [[David Sadler (footballer)|David Sadler]], a former OPGS student who went on to play 272 games for [[Manchester United]] football club following the devastating [[Munich air disaster]], and 4 games for England)\n* Wilberforce (named after [[William Wilberforce]], the famous British politician who successfully stood against slavery, who has family in [[East Farleigh]])\n\n==Headmasters==\n* 2006 \u2013 Kevin W. Moody\n* 1992 \u2013 2006 Mike J. Newbould\n* 1985 \u2013 1992 A. G. Sandford\n* 1966 \u2013 1985 John A. Skinner\n* 1956 \u2013 1966 R. H. Voice\n* 1933 \u2013 1955 H. Collins\n* 1918 \u2013 1933 James Quick\n\n==Alumni==\nOPGS has helped nurture students through various career paths.\n* [[James Hall (gymnast)|James Hall]] Artistic gymnast<ref name=\"James Hall\">{{cite web|title=James Hall |url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/oakwood-park-pupil-james-hall-ha-a56625}}</ref>\n* [[David Sadler (footballer)|David Sadler]] A footballer for Manchester United\n* [[Dominic Sherwood]] Actor, known for his roles in [[Shadowhunters]] and [[Vampire Academy (film)|Vampire Academy]]\n* Laurie Vincent Musician, known for playing Guitar, Bass and Vocals in the band [[Slaves (UK band)|Slaves]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/news/slaves-nominated-for-bbc-music-sound-of-2015-28022/|title=Maidstone band shortlisted for prestigious award|work=Kent Online|access-date=17 April 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Marc Morris]] Historian\n* [[Mark Sargeant]] Michelin starred chef\n\n==Sex Tape==\nOPGS hit the headlines on 22 June 1995 when pupils using a 'blank' VHS tape for a project found it contained footage of a male chemistry teacher and a female physics teacher engaging in sexual acts in the school's gymnasium. Pupils reportedly had to be instructed not to speak to the sizeable number of journalists who congregated at the school gates.<ref>{{cite news|title=Teachers axed for sex video|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/salamandertome/3319960197/sizes/l/in/set-72157614630872064/|newspaper=[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]|date=22 June 1995}}</ref>\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.opgs.org Oakwood Park Grammar School website]\n* [http://www.opgs.net/ Oakwood Park Grammar School alumni network]\n\n{{Schools in Kent}}\n\n[[Category:Grammar schools in Kent]]\n[[Category:Boys' schools in Kent]]\n[[Category:Maidstone]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1918]]\n[[Category:1918 establishments in E